How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses.
Unless a user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a two-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched on computers, and the winner, like a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a phase of file mapping, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "hatch" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular print (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, the other nodes easily verify that it is good.
The transaction is then indestructible linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the print.
If, for fraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orpheline because the two have different prints.
