In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators made up of Islamic students took over the US embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats in hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled after the revolution to the United States, who had been supporting his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, and it could not, in fact, abandon Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, even worsened later by the failure of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations by the Algerian government.
Their luck in the United States sparked a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian feeling.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and stager Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory in America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated areas, they were found in the Canadian Ambassador's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a tour team to make repairs to a large-scale science-fiction film.
Combination of genders
The expert's plan in exfiltration Tony Mendez requires Hollywood collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company and offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way, but also a "caper motion", the story of a successful blow, a betrayal - such as in the trilogy of Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
Ambience follows: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (sub-title sequences contain iconic photographs of the time of the events and the way in which these photos have been retransscribed into the film, there are no major differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with customary men discussing the situation around conference tables, in corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to relaunch his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected actor and his actor's game ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long-distance after the police shadow " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The Town" (2010).
It's also Afleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of a place's atmosphere is one of the features that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role is "maintained" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity that also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false tour team in the Tehran Basar).
Too many actions in too many locations
The stager had to content himself with a subject that offered only a few palpitating scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
