Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the request of Palestinians to obtain observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstinence.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be careful because it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, however, without showing too much criticism of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain when voting on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Furthermore, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
Thus, the Germans meet on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still struggling to find this role, but they're on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
External policy, such as in France or Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean specifically for Germans?
It shows the will to adopt independent positions of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected Germany's position towards the conflict in the Middle East and the abstention of the United Nations in its vote?
Germany first has important openings in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to distort public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is certainly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But it is a decisive element in the German strategic reflections.
Does Germany sleep in its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in major votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do they differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly demonstrating a great deal of understanding of the European position.
However, given the country's political configuration, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that real differences of opinion are not so big as they always seem.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from enthusiastically about Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes things any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore join a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will play a role as a locomotive in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been sensitive.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that is more marked by their independence.
Does Germany see itself as an actor of weight on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it always difficult to take on top roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look at, for example, the euro crisis, we note that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with very varied neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy only decreases, but at this point the EU does not fill this gap, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy of Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America analyse together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
