Unasur's summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, although it had been announced previously and theoretically adopted by the 7 current deputies.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Regular Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unassur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency reported that it would be released after the close of the summit and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian Government's website.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief press statements.
Access by journalists to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that was circulating among journalists was reported by the press attachments of some of the Unasur governments that attended your meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only paper released during the day was the list of the presidents present, which caused a certain malaise among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media that claimed more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the speech of President Humala and not of the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the 3rd South American Summit of the Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested by the press, it did not disseminate the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to establish secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited the availability of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which runs a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, met at your regional meeting and stated that they would respect the IJC's decision to hear the complainants from both sides in the trial that Lima tried against Santiago and that began Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are having today before this international court," said President Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
" Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country in accordance with international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international tribunals," President Pinyera added by handing out a hand to President Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit itself to the decisions of this international court, after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be a serious mistake.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Roseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended by Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its former President Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
He read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 project action lines had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he noted that the countries of Unasur would put in place "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He reported that actions would be put in place to improve “cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to drugs, access to the Internet at low prices throughout South America, and to assess the risks of natural disasters jointly and effectively.”
With a crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (from Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should help to increase our productive matrix and create a better future for our people," said President Humala.
"We have decided to favour a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by joining our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian President said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the cross-roads of its territory, from coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentions the political situation of Paraguay.
"We hope that the country's electoral process will allow it to be reintegrated into the South American Union," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he was hoping to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, next Saturday in Mexico to discuss peacefully the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the Treaty with Nicaragua, which will call for a discussion with this country," he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," President Santos added.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they planned to attend the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto.
