Hector "Hetin" Reyes "The basketball is all my life"
The basketball balloon "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the ground and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of the local basketball as large as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage does not condemn him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes has been immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, which is as a player of lower leagues, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or as president of the basketball federation.
"I've been wearing several basketball helmets all my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes on a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"The basketball is my whole life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind him of his route out of standard, testify to it.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he most loves are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as co-manager or team manager.
"That was my best years, the ones I've enjoyed most because I've had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has led to many years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead in the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been leading here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a player cost you two meters.
Do you want it?"
It's like starting Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gauss, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gauss was going to help us try and win another one.
He enjoyed the Vaqueros Championship with Gaussian, but only at a distance since he was already the great manipulator of the federation in 1988.
At that time, he would prefer to take advantage of his duties and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the World of 1990, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not given us the last match, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Team the best national team you've ever seen?
It is one of the best, as was the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is that of the Cuban Pan-American Games in 1991, when we won gold and that we put a link to the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that had won bronze during the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculin" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colon and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not attend the world of 90 due to a knee problem.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and a great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament of Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruiter in place of the players suspended by the imbroglio of the American Games of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all the predictions.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
No doubt it's Piculin Ortiz.
Its statistics at the international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculin did.
And this without taking into account his route in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very difficult to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I love the work that Leo Ariel does.
For you, what is your greatest success within the federation?
It was part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that at the beginning of the 1990s BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What are you still doing?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as regionalization of minor categories.
For example, Ponce boys play only in their area and face only teams from the other corners of the island at national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of compulsory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and arbitrators.
That makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch videos from my time on YouTube, I enjoy my little kids and, from time to time, I watch basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy my wife's company, Isabel, which has always been on my side.
